            <section class="block block-block block-block-16 block-even clearfix">

        <h3 class="block-title">News &amp; Events</h3>
    
      <h4><a href="http://www.bpl.bc.ca/news/cameron-branch-renovations" title="Cameron Branch renovations">Cameron Branch renovations</a></h4><p>The branch closure is extended to September 19. Learn about available services during the extended closure.</p><h4><a href="http://www.bpl.bc.ca/have-you-recently-received-your-canadian-citizenship" title="Cultural Access Pass">Cultural Access Pass</a></h4><p>Are you a new Canadian citizen? Get your Cultural Access Pass and visit more than 600 cultural attractions across Canada, all for free!</p><h4><a title="NewToBC.ca" href="http://newtobc.ca/">NewToBC</a></h4><p>NewToBC unites 10 public library systems in Metro Vancouver to help connect newcomers with programs and services in their community.</p><h4><a title="Metrotown transit notice" href="/news/metrotown-transit-notice">Metrotown transit notice</a></h4><p>The elevator at the Metrotown SkyTrain station is out of service until Winter 2017, due to station upgrades.</p>  
</section>  <section class="block block-views block-views-we-recommend-block-2 block-odd clearfix">

        <h3 class="block-title">We Recommend...</h3>
    
      <div class="view view-we-recommend view-id-we_recommend view-display-id-block_2 view-dom-id-2add2a0273a5c26d6464a751bf18555d">
        
  
  
      <div class="view-content">
        <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first">
      
          <div><a href="https://burnaby.bibliocommons.com/item/show/1142398002"><img src="http://www.bpl.bc.ca/sites/default/files/styles/we_recommend/public/uploads/materials/images/exposure.jpg?itok=BZWeBZDm" width="72" height="110" alt="Exposure, by Helen Dunmore" /></a></div>    
          <h4 class="term-link"><a href="https://burnaby.bibliocommons.com/item/show/1142398002">Exposure</a></h4>    
  <div>        <em>Helen Dunmore</em>  </div>  
  <div class="views-field views-field-body">        <div class="field-content"><p>London, November, 1960: the Cold War is at its height. Spy fever fills the newspapers, and the political establishment knows how and where to bury its secrets. When a highly sensitive file goes missing, Simon Callington is accused of passing information to the Soviets, and arrested. His wife, Lily, suspects that his imprisonment is part of a cover-up, and that more powerful men than Simon will do anything to prevent their own downfall. But what she does not realise is that Simon has hidden vital truths about his past, and may be found guilty of another crime that carries with it an even greater penalty.</p></div>  </div>  
  <div class="views-field views-field-edit-node">        <span class="field-content"></span>  </div>  </div>
  <div class="views-row views-row-2 views-row-even views-row-last">
      
          <div><a href="https://burnaby.bibliocommons.com/item/show/1005629002"><img src="http://www.bpl.bc.ca/sites/default/files/styles/we_recommend/public/uploads/materials/images/boys-in-the-boat.jpg?itok=19LPDgHY" width="72" height="109" alt="The Boys in the Boat, by Daniel Brown" /></a></div>    
          <h4 class="term-link"><a href="https://burnaby.bibliocommons.com/item/show/1005629002">The Boys in the Boat</a></h4>    
  <div>        <em>Daniel Brown</em>  </div>  
  <div class="views-field views-field-body">        <div class="field-content"><p>Daniel James Brown's robust book tells the story of the University of Washington's 1936 eight-oar crew and their epic quest for an Olympic gold medal, a team that transformed the sport and grabbed the attention of millions of Americans. The sons of loggers, shipyard workers, and farmers, the boys defeated elite rivals first from eastern US and British universities and finally the German crew rowing for Adolf Hitler in the Olympic games in Berlin, 1936.</p></div>  </div>  
  <div class="views-field views-field-edit-node">        <span class="field-content"></span>  </div>  </div>
    </div>
  
  
  
      
